DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines the theoretical relationship between cognitive offloading research and extended mind debates. A central question is whether offloading phenomena provide evidence for or against extended cognition. Some scholars argue that offloading demonstrates functional integration between agents and tools, supporting constitutive extension claims. Others contend that offloading is better explained as embedded cognition - using external resources without cognitive constitution. Recent work by Britten-Neish (2025) connects offloading to action theory, arguing that Anscombean accounts of agency support extended mind interpretations. Hutchins' distributed cognition framework (2010) provides an alternative to both internalist and extended mind approaches, emphasizing cognitive ecology. The debate increasingly focuses on degrees of integration rather than binary distinctions, with second-wave extended mind theories proposing gradient accounts of cognitive extension.

Key theoretical tensions include: the parity principle versus complementarity hypothesis, whether offloading involves genuine cognitive processes or merely causal scaffolding, and how to interpret empirical findings about strategy selection in offloading tasks. Contemporary work explores whether cognitive integration admits of degrees (Heersmink), how offloading relates to enactivism (Sganzerla et al. 2025), and whether distributed cognition provides a better framework than extended mind for understanding offloading phenomena.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses how philosophers interpret empirical offloading research and whether such findings support extended mind claims. It covers debates about cognitive boundaries, functional integration criteria, and alternative frameworks for understanding mind-world coupling. These theoretical disputes shape how offloading evidence is interpreted and whether it counts as evidence for cognitive extension.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited explicit discussion of specific offloading paradigms (intention offloading, metacognitive offloading) in philosophical analyses. Few papers directly compare predictions from extended mind versus embedded cognition frameworks. Missing systematic treatment of how different offloading strategies (metamemory-based versus perceptual-motor) relate to extension claims. Eight entries marked INCOMPLETE (no abstracts available): Michaelian & Sutton (2013), Facchin & Leonetti (2024), Hardy-Vallée & Payette (2008), Spitzer (2016), Deane et al. (2017), Dodig-Crnkovic (2018), Krueger (2018), Wijermans et al. (2008).

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Focus on how different theoretical frameworks interpret the same offloading phenomena differently. Emphasize methodological debates about what counts as evidence for cognitive constitution versus mere causal influence. Track the evolution from first-wave (parity-based) to second-wave (integration-based) extended mind arguments in relation to offloading.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Extended Mind Supporters (6 papers): Offloading demonstrates cognitive constitution when integration criteria are met
- Distributed Cognition Alternatives (4 papers): Cognitive ecology framework better explains offloading without constitution claims
- Enactivist Critiques (3 papers): Extension claims neglect active sense-making processes central to cognition
- Skeptical/Embedded (3 papers): Offloading shows causal scaffolding but not cognitive constitution
- Gradient/Integration Accounts (2 papers): Degrees of cognitive integration rather than binary boundaries
====================================================================
